odynamics|last=Bejan|first=Adrian|publisher=Wiley|year=2016|isbn=978-1-119-05209-8|edition=4|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|author=Cengel, Yunus A., & Boles, Michael A.|title=Thermodynamics \u2013 an Engineering Approach|publisher=McGraw Hill|year=2002|isbn=978-0-07-238332-4|location=|pages=|oclc=45791449|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/thermodynamicsen00ceng_0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Dunning-Davies, Jeremy|title=Concise Thermodynamics: Principles and Applications|publisher=Horwood Publishing|year=1997|isbn=978-1-8985-6315-0|location=|pages=|oclc=36025958}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Kroemer, Herbert|author2=Kittel, Charles|lastauthoramp=yes|title=Thermal Physics|publisher=W.H. Freeman Company|year=1980|isbn=978-0-7167-1088-2|location=|pages=|oclc=32932988}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikibooks|Engineering Thermodynamics}}\n{{wikiquote|Thermodynamics}}\n* {{cite EB1911 |title=Thermodynamics |volume=26 |pages=808\u2013814 |short=x |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabri26chisrich/page/808}}\n* [http://tigger.uic.edu/~mansoori/Thermodynamic.Data.and.Property_html  Thermodynamics Data & Property Calculation Websites]\n* [http://tigger.uic.edu/~mansoori/Thermodynamics.Educational.Sites_html Thermodynamics Educational Websites]\n* [http://scienceworld.wolfram.com/physics/topics/Thermodynamics.html Thermodynamics at ''ScienceWorld'']\n* [http://www.wiley.com/legacy/college/boyer/0470003790/reviews/thermo/thermo_intro.htm Biochemistry Thermodynamics]\n* [http://farside.ph.utexas.edu/teaching/sm1/lectures/lectures.html Thermodynamics and Statistical Mechanics]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090430200028/http://www.ent.ohiou.edu/~thermo/ Engineering Thermodynamics \u2013 A Graphical Approach]\n* [http://farside.ph.utexas.edu/teaching/sm1/statmech.pdf Thermodynamics and Statistical Mechanics] by Richard Fitzpatrick\n\n{{Physics-footer}}\n{{HVAC}}\n\n[[Category:Thermodynamics| ]]\n[[Category:Chemical engineering]]\n[[Category:Concepts in physics]]\n[[Category:Subfields of physics]]\n", "name_user": "OrdinaryArtery", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistical mechanics:Removed extra period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermodynamics"}
{"title_page": "Restaurant Opportunities Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Restaurant Opportunities Center\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = Jessica Wynter Martin - RaiseTheWage, 2016.jpg\n| image_size          = 250\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = 21st April 2016 - Washington, D.C. - U.S. Secretary of Labor Thomas Perez participates in a press conference with congressional leaders to discuss the importance of raising the federal minimum wage and urging Congress to pass the Murray-Scott Raise the Wage legislation. Jessica Wynter Martin, Worker (Restaurant Opportunities Center United)\n| logo                =\n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = ROC\n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = 2004\n| founder             = [[Saru Jayaraman]], Fekkak Mamdouh\n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = Not-for-profit\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = To improve wages and working conditions for the nation's low wage restaurant workforce\n| headquarters        = \n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = United States\n| services            = \n| products            = \n| methods             = \n| fields              = \n| membership          = 13000\n| membership_year     = 2013\n| language            = \n| owner               = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| slogan              = \n| mission             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Restaurant Opportunities Centers United''' (ROC) is a [[not-for-profit organization]] and [[worker center]] with affiliates in a number of cities across the United States. Its mission is to improve wages and working conditions for the nation's low wage restaurant workforce. Its tactics and strategy have drawn fire from business groups and restaurant industry lobbyists.<ref name=\"eatocracy.cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://eatocracy.cnn.com/2013/05/31/a-restaurant-designed-to-support-an-industry/|title=Eatocracy - CNN|website=CNN|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/17/business/as-worker-advocacy-groups-gain-momentum-businesses-fight-back.html?_r=1 | title=Advocates for Workers Raise the Ire of Business | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 16, 2014 | accessdate=26 January 2014 | author=Greenhouse, Steven}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2013, ROC claimed to represent 13,000 restaurant workers, 100 employers and 2,000 consumer members in 32 cities across the United States.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Activist-at-vanguard-of-restaurant-workers-rights-5135081.php|title=Activist at vanguard of restaurant workers' rights|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe group was founded with funding from multiple foundations with a stated goal to \u201corganize all unorganized restaurant workers in New York City.\u201d<ref name=\"DAS\">{{cite news|last=La Botz|first=Dan|title=Immigrant Restaurant Workers Hope to Rock New York|url=http://www.dollarsandsense.org/archives/2004/0104labotz.html|date=January\u2013February 2004|accessdate=December 11, 2012|newspaper=Dollars & Sense}}</ref> ROC-NY was founded by immigration attorney [[Saru Jayaraman]] and [[Windows on the World]] waiter Fekkak Mamdouh and other restaurant workers who survived the [[September 11 attacks]] on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in 2001<ref name=\"DAS\"/> to provide support for the displaced workers, including undocumented immigrants. These workers had worked in restaurants in the WTC, including in the [[Windows on the World]] restaurant located on its top floors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dobnik|first=Verena|title=Restaurant workers look through new Windows|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jFgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JcgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5071,1324324&dq=restaurant-opportunities-center&hl=en|newspaper=Times Daily|date=September 10, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"RNN\">The Real News Network, 11 November  2011, [http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=7582 \"9/11 Survivors Create Worker Owned Restaurants 9/11: Restaurant worker survivors open fair wage businesses\"]</ref>\n\nJayaraman is author of Behind the Kitchen Door (2013), a book that follows the lives of restaurant workers in eight American cities, seeking to call attention to their low wages, along with unfair labor practices, exploitation, and unsanitary kitchen practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.kqed.org/bayareabites/2013/03/21/what-goes-on-behind-the-kitchen-door/ |title=What Goes on Behind the Kitchen Door : Bay Area Bites |publisher=Blogs.kqed.org |date= |accessdate=2018-05-20}}</ref>\n\nMamdouh is the co-author, with [[Rinku Sen]], of The Accidental American: Immigration and Citizenship in the Era of Global Immigration (2008), a book that argues for a free flow of international labor to match globalization\u2019s free flow of capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imagine2050.newcomm.org/2009/11/10/book-review-the-accidental-american/|title=Book Review: The Accidental American - IMAGINE 2050|date=10 November 2009|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe March 2013 announcement by [[Richard L. Trumka]], president of the [[AFL-CIO]], that organized labor would work more closely groups focusing on aid immigrant workers is one factor in the decision by business groups to target ROC.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nROC supports the Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sandiegofreepress.org/2013/09/raise-the-sub-minimum-wage/|title=Raise the Sub-Minimum Wage|date=22 September 2013|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nROC is a target of the [[National Restaurant Association]] and allied lobbyists like [[Richard Berman]].<ref name=\"wood\">{{cite news |last1=Wood |first1=Marjorie E. |title=Tipping the Scales of Inequality |url=https://otherwords.org/tipping-scales-inequality-minimum-wage-restaurants/ |accessdate=29 January 2019 |publisher=[[Institute for Policy Studies]] |work=OtherWords |date=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n{{see also|Tipped wage}}\n\nROC conducts labor campaigns to encourage restaurant owners to increase wages and change working conditions for employees.<ref>{{cite news|last=London|first=Paul A.|title=Good News: Restaurants Are Hiring|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/paul-a-london/good-news-restaurants-are_b_1892016.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=September 18, 2012|accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Also, ROC provides free training in all areas of restaurant work for restaurant workers and workers seeking employment.<ref>Restaurant Opportunities Center of New York, [http://rocny.org/what-we-do \"What We Do\"] accessed November 11, 2011</ref>\n\nIn early 2012, ROC launched its \"Dignity at Darden\" campaign, targeting what it alleged to be discrimination and [[wage theft]] by [[Darden Restaurants]], which owns and operates such chains as [[Red Lobster (restaurant)|Red Lobster]], [[Olive Garden]], [[LongHorn Steakhouse]] and [[Capital Grille]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutchicago.com/restaurants-bars/15103779/restaurant-opportunities-centers-united-launch-campaign-to-improve-jobs-in|title=Restaurant Opportunities Centers United launch campaign to improve restaurant industry jobs|website=Time Out Chicago|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corp-research.org/darden|title=Darden Restaurants: Corporate Rap Sheet - Corporate Research Project|website=www.corp-research.org|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>  In the Darden campaign, ROC charged that in addition to paying the lowest wages possible to Darden employees (as low as $2.13 per hour), not providing health insurance or [[sick leave|paid sick days]] for a workforce of 200,000 people, the company was also an opponent of paid sick day legislation providing for a low-wage worker to stay at home and recover instead of going to work sick, which led to public exposure to hepatitis A and other medical threats.<ref>http://restaurant-hospitality.com/hrlegal/labor-activists-try-scare-tactics-darden</ref>\n\nROC organizers appeared at Darden's 2012 annual shareholder's meeting to advance their complaints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-09-18/news/os-darden-shareholders-meeting-20120918_1_darden-restaurants-clarence-otis-darden-s-ceo|title=Workers grill Darden Restaurants CEO at shareholders meeting|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nROC dropped the lawsuit in mid-2012.<ref>http://www.equality-law.co.uk/news/2308/66/US-Restaurant-workers-group-drops-racial-discrimination-charges-against-Darden/</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, in an unrelated lawsuit, 20,000 former and current Darden workers joined a federal lawsuit alleging that the company underpaid them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2014-01-09/business/os-darden-lawsuit-20140109_1_darden-restaurants-lawsuit-plaintiffs|title=Almost 20,000 join Darden Restaurants lawsuit|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nThe organization also undertakes research on the state of the food industry with a special focus on issues that affect food workers. ROC's more than 15 [http://rocunited.org/research-resources/ published reports] have been [http://rocunited.org/news/roc-in-the-news/ widely cited and covered by media]. ROC says that in its \u201cDiners\u2019 Guide\u201d it promotes workplace \"best practices\" that serve as models for employers to facilitate business profitability while treating employees fairly.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fabio|last=Parasecoli|title=Not Your Usual Restaurant Reviews|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/fabio-parasecoli/restaurant-opportunity-center-2013-dining-guide_b_2478675.html|date=2013-01-15|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref> The methodology of the report states that when rating national chains that did not respond at the corporate level or were franchised, ROC only called individual locations in four Southern states.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Restaurant Opportunities Center|title=Diners\u2019 Guide|url=http://rocunited.org/dinersguide/|year=2013|accessdate=2013-02-14|page=31}}</ref>  The report did not list the survey questions asked of the restaurants in the study or the individuals that researchers spoke with to obtain the survey answers.\n\nIn a 2010 report, ROC related that 90% of 4,000 restaurant workers surveyed between 2003 and 2010 reported not receiving health insurance through their employer, while 61.5% reported that they had no insurance at all.<ref name=\"eatocracy.cnn.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocunited.org/publications/roc-serving-while-sick/|title=Serving While Sick|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Expansion==\nSince its founding, ROC has expanded to 32 cities across the country with more than 13,000 restaurant workers, 100 employers and 2,000 consumers claimed as members.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\"/> Restaurant Opportunities Centers United was founded in January 2008 following a national restaurant workers' convention that took place in Chicago in August 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us: Our History|url=http://rocunited.org/about-us/our-history/|publisher=Restaurant Opportunities Centers United|accessdate=April 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510141614/http://rocunited.org/about-us/our-history/|archivedate=May 10, 2012}}</ref> ROC has affiliate offices in New York, D.C, Miami, Philadelphia, Los Angeles, Houston, New Orleans, Detroit, Chicago, Oakland, and Pittsburgh.\n\n==COLORS restaurants==\nROC-NY also helped create a worker-owned restaurant called [[Colors (restaurant)|COLORS]] in New York City,<ref name=nypost2006-01-06/> in an effort to demonstrate that a restaurant that treats employees fairly can still be profitable. The restaurant, according to critics, has been a consistent money loser, is closed to the public for long stretches, and has received multiple citations from the New York City Health Department for \"critical violations.\"<ref name=rocexposed>{{cite web | url = http://www.rocexposed.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ROC_TheCOLORofHypocrisy_finalv2.pdf | title = The COLOR of Hypocrisy: ROC\u2019s Failed Restaurant Model | publisher = | archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224142048/http://www.rocexposed.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ROC_TheCOLORofHypocrisy_finalv2.pdf | archivedate = 2014-02-24 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2018-05-20 | quote = The flagship COLORS New York location is now closed for service, but even as COLORS was failing to turn a profit, ROC was actively hoisting COLORS as a model restaurant and attacking other restaurateurs for the way they conducted themselves. }}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant also serves as a training facility for students in ROC's training sessions for skills.<ref name=DissentSpring2012>\n{{cite news | url = http://www.dissentmagazine.org/article/high-end-food-low-wage-labor|title=High-End Food, Low-Wage Labor | author = Laurie Woolever | date = Spring 2012 | work = [[Dissent (American magazine)|Dissent magazine]] | accessdate  = 20 May 2018 | quote = Among its many initiatives are two worker-owned and run restaurants, in New York City and Detroit, both called COLORS, that provide job skills training. COLORS rents part of its restaurant space to ROC, which provides worker training, an arrangement that in turn allows COLORS to pay its employees a sustainable wage. }}</ref>  ROC-Michigan opened a COLORS restaurant in downtown Detroit in September 2011.<ref>Detroit News, [http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20120202/OPINION03/202020315 \"Colors-Detroit cooks up good food and training opportunities\"] accessed November 8, 2012</ref><ref>Huffington Post, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/colors-detroit-restaurant_n_1198675.html5 \"COLORS-Detroit Restaurant Cooks Up Local Foods, Labor Rights\"] accessed November 20, 2012</ref>\n\n==Attacks==\n\nWashington lobbyist [[Richard Berman]], of [[Berman and Company]] and the [[Center for Consumer Freedom]] has taken out full-page ads attacking ROC and set up a website attacking its work.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>  Berman's [[Employment Policies Institute]] produces reports used by  restaurant industry groups in their lobbying campaign against the increase in the minimum wage, although the quality and reliability of such reports has been contested by academics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/10/us/politics/fight-over-minimum-wage-illustrates-web-of-industry-ties.html|title=Fight Over Minimum Wage Illustrates Web of Industry Ties|date=9 February 2014|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2007, ROC was sued by its worker-owners for matters related to the profit that will come from the restaurant Colors, and requiring them to pay monthly dues, attend protests, and lobby for ROC causes and other unrelated causes, including against the war in Iraq. The workers that objected were fired by Saru Jayaraman, although all claims in the lawsuit were dismissed by the court.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elliott|first=Tom|title=\"Social Justice\" Hypocrites|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/opinion/opedcolumnists/item_6hT516aUFQpglJLPWB6zXJ|newspaper=New York Post|date=March 22, 2007}}</ref><ref>All claims in the lawsuit were dismissed by the court;see decision: Godoy v. Restaurant Opportunity Center of New York,  615 F.Supp.2d 186 (S.D.N.Y. 2009).</ref>\nIn 2010 it was reported that COLORS New York was \u201cstruggling to pay its bills, and it's sorting out management problems dating back to its inception.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last=Fickenscher|first=Lisa|title=True Colors|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20100627/SUB/306279997|newspaper=Crain\u2019s New York|date= 2010-06-27|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\nU.S. Congressman Darrell Issa (R-CA), chairman of the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, wrote in a letter to Secretary of Labor Hilda Solis that Colors in New York City had a \"troubling history of poor sanitation.\"<ref>New York Post, [http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/pressure_cookers_VEWVCvvHxYUjuEkDgRcWON \"House probes NY restaurant-harass group\"] accessed November 12, 2012</ref> In addition, the House Committee on Education and the Workforce is investigating whether ROC should be subject to federal labor laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edworkforce.house.gov/uploadedfiles/08-26-13_dol_response.pdf|title=House Committee Letter|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=nypost2006-01-06>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.nypost.com/p/news/item_4a0xaRG1vVPUUcXh3q7xYL \n| title       = WINDOWS' BACK OPEN - 9/11 SURVIVORS LAUNCH EATERY\n| work        = [[New York Post]]\n| author      = Leonard Greene\n| date        = 2006-01-06\n| accessdate  = 2012-11-20\n| quote       = When Colors opened last night at 417 Lafayette St., in the heart of NoHo, it brought to life the aspirations of many of those who perished in the terror attacks that brought down the Twin Towers.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sources==\n:*[http://washingtonexaminer.com/big-labors-big-gamble-on-restaurant-opportunities-center/article/2536194 Big Labor Gambles on Restaurant Opportunity, ''Washington Examiner'']\n:*[https://nypost.com/2012/07/03/house-probes-ny-restaurant-harass-group/ House Probes New York Restaurant Group, ''New York Post'']\n:*[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2013/12/03/restaurant-union-serving-up-protests-for-higher-wages/ \"Restaurant Union Serving Up Protests,\" Fox News]\n:*[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/14/tipped-over-the-edge_n_1276376.html \"Tipped over the Edge,\" Huffington Post]\n:*[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/06/darden-discrimination-suit_n_1257293.html \"Darden Discrimination Suit,\"Huffington Post]\n:*[http://www.philly.com/philly/food/Fat_Salmon_workers_settle_wage_dispute.html \"Fat Salmon Workers Settle Wage Dispute,\"Philly.com]\n:*[http://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2013/11/25/Protestors-briefly-block-supply-entrance-to-The-Capital-Grille/stories/201311250142 \"Protesters Briefly Block Supply Entrance,\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'']\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rocny.org/ Restaurant Opportunities Center of New York website]\n*[http://rocunited.org/ Restaurant Opportunities Centers United website]\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2002]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Restaurant Opportunities Center\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = Jessica Wynter Martin - RaiseTheWage, 2016.jpg\n| image_size          = 250\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = 21st April 2016 - Washington, D.C. - U.S. Secretary of Labor Thomas Perez participates in a press conference with congressional leaders to discuss the importance of raising the federal minimum wage and urging Congress to pass the Murray-Scott Raise the Wage legislation. Jessica Wynter Martin, Worker (Restaurant Opportunities Center United)\n| logo                =\n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = ROC\n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = 2004\n| founder             = [[Saru Jayaraman]], Fekkak Mamdouh\n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = Not-for-profit\n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = To improve wages and working conditions for the nation's low wage restaurant workforce\n| headquarters        = \n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = United States\n| services            = \n| products            = \n| methods             = \n| fields              = \n| membership          = 13000\n| membership_year     = 2013\n| language            = \n| owner               = <!-- or | owners = -->\n| sec_gen             = \n| leader_title        = \n| leader_name         = \n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| slogan              = \n| mission             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Restaurant Opportunities Centers United''' (ROC) is a [[not-for-profit organization]] and [[worker center]] with affiliates in a number of cities across the United States. Its mission is to improve wages and working conditions for the nation's low wage restaurant workforce. Its tactics and strategy have drawn fire from business groups and restaurant industry lobbyists.<ref name=\"eatocracy.cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://eatocracy.cnn.com/2013/05/31/a-restaurant-designed-to-support-an-industry/|title=Eatocracy - CNN|website=CNN|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/17/business/as-worker-advocacy-groups-gain-momentum-businesses-fight-back.html?_r=1 | title=Advocates for Workers Raise the Ire of Business | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 16, 2014 | accessdate=26 January 2014 | author=Greenhouse, Steven}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2013, ROC claimed to represent 13,000 restaurant workers, 100 employers and 2,000 consumer members in 32 cities across the United States.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Activist-at-vanguard-of-restaurant-workers-rights-5135081.php|title=Activist at vanguard of restaurant workers' rights|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe group was founded with funding from multiple foundations with a stated goal to \u201corganize all unorganized restaurant workers in New York City.\u201d<ref name=\"DAS\">{{cite news|last=La Botz|first=Dan|title=Immigrant Restaurant Workers Hope to Rock New York|url=http://www.dollarsandsense.org/archives/2004/0104labotz.html|date=January\u2013February 2004|accessdate=December 11, 2012|newspaper=Dollars & Sense}}</ref> ROC-NY was founded by immigration attorney [[Saru Jayaraman]] and [[Windows on the World]] waiter Fekkak Mamdouh and other restaurant workers who survived the [[September 11 attacks]] on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in 2001<ref name=\"DAS\"/> to provide support for the displaced workers, including undocumented immigrants. These workers had worked in restaurants in the WTC, including in the [[Windows on the World]] restaurant located on its top floors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dobnik|first=Verena|title=Restaurant workers look through new Windows|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jFgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JcgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5071,1324324&dq=restaurant-opportunities-center&hl=en|newspaper=Times Daily|date=September 10, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"RNN\">The Real News Network, 11 November  2011, [http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=7582 \"9/11 Survivors Create Worker Owned Restaurants 9/11: Restaurant worker survivors open fair wage businesses\"]</ref>\n\nJayaraman is author of Behind the Kitchen Door (2013), a book that follows the lives of restaurant workers in eight American cities, seeking to call attention to their low wages, along with unfair labor practices, exploitation, and unsanitary kitchen practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.kqed.org/bayareabites/2013/03/21/what-goes-on-behind-the-kitchen-door/ |title=What Goes on Behind the Kitchen Door : Bay Area Bites |publisher=Blogs.kqed.org |date= |accessdate=2018-05-20}}</ref>\n\nMamdouh is the co-author, with [[Rinku Sen]], of The Accidental American: Immigration and Citizenship in the Era of Global Immigration (2008), a book that argues for a free flow of international labor to match globalization\u2019s free flow of capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imagine2050.newcomm.org/2009/11/10/book-review-the-accidental-american/|title=Book Review: The Accidental American - IMAGINE 2050|date=10 November 2009|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe March 2013 announcement by [[Richard L. Trumka]], president of the [[AFL-CIO]], that organized labor would work more closely groups focusing on aid immigrant workers is one factor in the decision by business groups to target ROC.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nROC supports the Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sandiegofreepress.org/2013/09/raise-the-sub-minimum-wage/|title=Raise the Sub-Minimum Wage|date=22 September 2013|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nROC is a target of the [[National Restaurant Association]] and allied lobbyists like [[Richard Berman]].<ref name=\"wood\">{{cite news |last1=Wood |first1=Marjorie E. |title=Tipping the Scales of Inequality |url=https://otherwords.org/tipping-scales-inequality-minimum-wage-restaurants/ |accessdate=29 January 2019 |publisher=[[Institute for Policy Studies]] |work=OtherWords |date=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n{{see also|Tipped wage}}\n\nROC conducts labor campaigns to encourage restaurant owners to increase wages and change working conditions for employees.<ref>{{cite news|last=London|first=Paul A.|title=Good News: Restaurants Are Hiring|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/paul-a-london/good-news-restaurants-are_b_1892016.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=September 18, 2012|accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Also, ROC provides free training in all areas of restaurant work for restaurant workers and workers seeking employment.<ref>Restaurant Opportunities Center of New York, [http://rocny.org/what-we-do \"What We Do\"] accessed November 11, 2011</ref>\n\nIn early 2012, ROC launched its \"Dignity at Darden\" campaign, targeting what it alleged to be discrimination and [[wage theft]] by [[Darden Restaurants]], which owns and operates such chains as [[Red Lobster (restaurant)|Red Lobster]], [[Olive Garden]], [[LongHorn Steakhouse]] and [[Capital Grille]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutchicago.com/restaurants-bars/15103779/restaurant-opportunities-centers-united-launch-campaign-to-improve-jobs-in|title=Restaurant Opportunities Centers United launch campaign to improve restaurant industry jobs|website=Time Out Chicago|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corp-research.org/darden|title=Darden Restaurants: Corporate Rap Sheet - Corporate Research Project|website=www.corp-research.org|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>  In the Darden campaign, ROC charged that in addition to paying the lowest wages possible to Darden employees (as low as $2.13 per hour), not providing health insurance or [[sick leave|paid sick days]] for a workforce of 200,000 people, the company was also an opponent of paid sick day legislation providing for a low-wage worker to stay at home and recover instead of going to work sick, which led to public exposure to hepatitis A and other medical threats.<ref>http://restaurant-hospitality.com/hrlegal/labor-activists-try-scare-tactics-darden</ref>\n\nROC organizers appeared at Darden's 2012 annual shareholder's meeting to advance their complaints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-09-18/news/os-darden-shareholders-meeting-20120918_1_darden-restaurants-clarence-otis-darden-s-ceo|title=Workers grill Darden Restaurants CEO at shareholders meeting|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nROC dropped the lawsuit in mid-2012.<ref>http://www.equality-law.co.uk/news/2308/66/US-Restaurant-workers-group-drops-racial-discrimination-charges-against-Darden/</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, in an unrelated lawsuit, 20,000 former and current Darden workers joined a federal lawsuit alleging that the company underpaid them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2014-01-09/business/os-darden-lawsuit-20140109_1_darden-restaurants-lawsuit-plaintiffs|title=Almost 20,000 join Darden Restaurants lawsuit|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nThe organization also undertakes research on the state of the food industry with a special focus on issues that affect food workers. ROC's more than 15 [http://rocunited.org/research-resources/ published reports] have been [http://rocunited.org/news/roc-in-the-news/ widely cited and covered by media]. ROC says that in its \u201cDiners\u2019 Guide\u201d it promotes workplace \"best practices\" that serve as models for employers to facilitate business profitability while treating employees fairly.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fabio|last=Parasecoli|title=Not Your Usual Restaurant Reviews|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/fabio-parasecoli/restaurant-opportunity-center-2013-dining-guide_b_2478675.html|date=2013-01-15|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref> The methodology of the report states that when rating national chains that did not respond at the corporate level or were franchised, ROC only called individual locations in four Southern states.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Restaurant Opportunities Center|title=Diners\u2019 Guide|url=http://rocunited.org/dinersguide/|year=2013|accessdate=2013-02-14|page=31}}</ref>  The report did not list the survey questions asked of the restaurants in the study or the individuals that researchers spoke with to obtain the survey answers.\n\nIn a 2010 report, ROC related that 90% of 4,000 restaurant workers surveyed between 2003 and 2010 reported not receiving health insurance through their employer, while 61.5% reported that they had no insurance at all.<ref name=\"eatocracy.cnn.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocunited.org/publications/roc-serving-while-sick/|title=Serving While Sick|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Expansion==\nSince its founding, ROC has expanded to 32 cities across the country with more than 13,000 restaurant workers, 100 employers and 2,000 consumers claimed as members.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\"/> Restaurant Opportunities Centers United was founded in January 2008 following a national restaurant workers' convention that took place in Chicago in August 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us: Our History|url=http://rocunited.org/about-us/our-history/|publisher=Restaurant Opportunities Centers United|accessdate=April 10, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510141614/http://rocunited.org/about-us/our-history/|archivedate=May 10, 2012}}</ref> ROC has affiliate offices in New York, D.C, Miami, Philadelphia, Los Angeles, Houston, New Orleans, Detroit, Chicago, Oakland, and Pittsburgh.\n\n==COLORS restaurants==\nROC-NY also helped create a worker-owned restaurant called [[Colors (restaurant)|COLORS]] in New York City,<ref name=nypost2006-01-06/> in an effort to demonstrate that a restaurant that treats employees fairly can still be profitable. The restaurant, according to critics, has been a consistent money loser, is closed to the public for long stretches, and has received multiple citations from the New York City Health Department for \"critical violations.\"<ref name=rocexposed>{{cite web | url = http://www.rocexposed.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ROC_TheCOLORofHypocrisy_finalv2.pdf | title = The COLOR of Hypocrisy: ROC\u2019s Failed Restaurant Model | publisher = | archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224142048/http://www.rocexposed.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ROC_TheCOLORofHypocrisy_finalv2.pdf | archivedate = 2014-02-24 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2018-05-20 | quote = The flagship COLORS New York location is now closed for service, but even as COLORS was failing to turn a profit, ROC was actively hoisting COLORS as a model restaurant and attacking other restaurateurs for the way they conducted themselves. }}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant also serves as a training facility for students in ROC's training sessions for skills.<ref name=DissentSpring2012>\n{{cite news | url = http://www.dissentmagazine.org/article/high-end-food-low-wage-labor|title=High-End Food, Low-Wage Labor | author = Laurie Woolever | date = Spring 2012 | work = [[Dissent magazine]] | accessdate  = 20 May 2018 | quote = Among its many initiatives are two worker-owned and run restaurants, in New York City and Detroit, both called COLORS, that provide job skills training. COLORS rents part of its restaurant space to ROC, which provides worker training, an arrangement that in turn allows COLORS to pay its employees a sustainable wage. }}</ref>  ROC-Michigan opened a COLORS restaurant in downtown Detroit in September 2011.<ref>Detroit News, [http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20120202/OPINION03/202020315 \"Colors-Detroit cooks up good food and training opportunities\"] accessed November 8, 2012</ref><ref>Huffington Post, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/11/colors-detroit-restaurant_n_1198675.html5 \"COLORS-Detroit Restaurant Cooks Up Local Foods, Labor Rights\"] accessed November 20, 2012</ref>\n\n==Attacks==\n\nWashington lobbyist [[Richard Berman]], of [[Berman and Company]] and the [[Center for Consumer Freedom]] has taken out full-page ads attacking ROC and set up a website attacking its work.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>  Berman's [[Employment Policies Institute]] produces reports used by  restaurant industry groups in their lobbying campaign against the increase in the minimum wage, although the quality and reliability of such reports has been contested by academics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/10/us/politics/fight-over-minimum-wage-illustrates-web-of-industry-ties.html|title=Fight Over Minimum Wage Illustrates Web of Industry Ties|date=9 February 2014|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2007, ROC was sued by its worker-owners for matters related to the profit that will come from the restaurant Colors, and requiring them to pay monthly dues, attend protests, and lobby for ROC causes and other unrelated causes, including against the war in Iraq. The workers that objected were fired by Saru Jayaraman, although all claims in the lawsuit were dismissed by the court.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elliott|first=Tom|title=\"Social Justice\" Hypocrites|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/opinion/opedcolumnists/item_6hT516aUFQpglJLPWB6zXJ|newspaper=New York Post|date=March 22, 2007}}</ref><ref>All claims in the lawsuit were dismissed by the court;see decision: Godoy v. Restaurant Opportunity Center of New York,  615 F.Supp.2d 186 (S.D.N.Y. 2009).</ref>\nIn 2010 it was reported that COLORS New York was \u201cstruggling to pay its bills, and it's sorting out management problems dating back to its inception.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last=Fickenscher|first=Lisa|title=True Colors|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20100627/SUB/306279997|newspaper=Crain\u2019s New York|date= 2010-06-27|accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\nU.S. Congressman Darrell Issa (R-CA), chairman of the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, wrote in a letter to Secretary of Labor Hilda Solis that Colors in New York City had a \"troubling history of poor sanitation.\"<ref>New York Post, [http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/pressure_cookers_VEWVCvvHxYUjuEkDgRcWON \"House probes NY restaurant-harass group\"] accessed November 12, 2012</ref> In addition, the House Committee on Education and the Workforce is investigating whether ROC should be subject to federal labor laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edworkforce.house.gov/uploadedfiles/08-26-13_dol_response.pdf|title=House Committee Letter|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=nypost2006-01-06>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.nypost.com/p/news/item_4a0xaRG1vVPUUcXh3q7xYL \n| title       = WINDOWS' BACK OPEN - 9/11 SURVIVORS LAUNCH EATERY\n| work        = [[New York Post]]\n| author      = Leonard Greene\n| date        = 2006-01-06\n| accessdate  = 2012-11-20\n| quote       = When Colors opened last night at 417 Lafayette St., in the heart of NoHo, it brought to life the aspirations of many of those who perished in the terror attacks that brought down the Twin Towers.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sources==\n:*[http://washingtonexaminer.com/big-labors-big-gamble-on-restaurant-opportunities-center/article/2536194 Big Labor Gambles on Restaurant Opportunity, ''Washington Examiner'']\n:*[https://nypost.com/2012/07/03/house-probes-ny-restaurant-harass-group/ House Probes New York Restaurant Group, ''New York Post'']\n:*[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2013/12/03/restaurant-union-serving-up-protests-for-higher-wages/ \"Restaurant Union Serving Up Protests,\" Fox News]\n:*[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/14/tipped-over-the-edge_n_1276376.html \"Tipped over the Edge,\" Huffington Post]\n:*[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/06/darden-discrimination-suit_n_1257293.html \"Darden Discrimination Suit,\"Huffington Post]\n:*[http://www.philly.com/philly/food/Fat_Salmon_workers_settle_wage_dispute.html \"Fat Salmon Workers Settle Wage Dispute,\"Philly.com]\n:*[http://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2013/11/25/Protestors-briefly-block-supply-entrance-to-The-Capital-Grille/stories/201311250142 \"Protesters Briefly Block Supply Entrance,\" ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'']\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rocny.org/ Restaurant Opportunities Center of New York website]\n*[http://rocunited.org/ Restaurant Opportunities Centers United website]\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2002]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDissent (disambiguation)(link changed toDissent (American magazine)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Restaurant_Opportunities_Center"}
{"title_page": "Donald Tosh", "text_new": "{{short description|British writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| name  = Donald Tosh\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|03|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|12|03|1935|03|16|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| occupation = [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n\n'''Donald Tosh''' (16 March 1935 \u2013 3 December 2019) was a [[BBC]] [[screenwriter]] who contributed to ''[[Doctor Who]]'' in 1965.<ref>[http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/scots-story-editor-donald-tosh-4281943 Story Editor Donald Tosh]</ref> He was the last surviving [[script editor]] and writer from the [[William Hartnell]] era.\n\n==Career==\nBefore working on ''Doctor Who'' Tosh was briefly script editor on the series ''[[Compact (TV series)|Compact]]'', and had helped to develop the show that eventually became ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01lk11h Donald Tosh on Coronation Street and Doctor Who]</ref>\n\nTosh was the [[script editor|story editor]] for the ''Doctor Who'' stories between ''[[The Time Meddler]]'' and ''[[The Massacre of St Bartholomew's Eve]]'', working with producers [[Verity Lambert]] and [[John Wiles]]. On Tosh's final story, ''[[The Massacre of St Bartholomew's Eve]]'' by [[John Lucarotti]], Tosh performed a substantial rewrite of the scripts, both to align them with historical accuracy and also to accommodate [[William Hartnell]]'s dual role as both the Doctor and the Abbot of Amboise.<ref>http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/doctor-who-story-editor-donald-4282399</ref> On the final episode the story editor's credit was given over to his successor [[Gerry Davis (screenwriter)|Gerry Davis]] and Tosh was co-credited.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/massacre/detail.shtml</ref>\n\nHe also performed an extensive re-write of ''[[The Celestial Toymaker]]'' by [[Brian Hayles]]. Most of this work, however, was in turn rewritten by Davis. Tosh claimed that the [[List of Doctor Who items#T|trilogic game]] was the sole retention from his version of the script.<ref>'Script editing Who: interview with Donald Tosh', ''Doctor Who Magazine''. No. 191</ref>\n\n==Post Television==\nAfter leaving television Tosh worked for a time for [[English Heritage]].  He was Head Custodian of [[Sherborne Castle|Sherborne Old Castle]], [[Dorset]] and [[St Mawes]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/doctor-who-story-editor-donald-4282399</ref> He retired to [[Essex]].\n\nIn 2013 he appeared as an extra in ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]'', a drama about the making of the William Hartnell era of ''Doctor Who'', made to commemorate the show's 50th anniversary. The programme did not, however, depict a version of him as a character.\n\nTosh died in December 2019 at the age of 84.<ref>[http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2019/12/donald-tosh-1935-2019.html Donald Tosh 1935\u20132019]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0869162}}\n{{Doctor Who}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tosh, Donald}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:British science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British soap opera writers]]\n[[Category:British television writers]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| name  = Donald Tosh\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|03|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|12|03|1935|03|16|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| occupation = [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n\n'''Donald Tosh''' (16 March 1935 \u2013 3 December 2019) was a [[BBC]] [[screenwriter]] who contributed to ''[[Doctor Who]]'' in 1965.<ref>[http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/scots-story-editor-donald-tosh-4281943 Story Editor Donald Tosh]</ref> He was the last surviving [[script editor]] and writer from the [[William Hartnell]] era.\n\n==Career==\nBefore working on ''Doctor Who'' Tosh was briefly script editor on the series ''[[Compact (TV series)|Compact]]'', and had helped to develop the show that eventually became ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01lk11h Donald Tosh on Coronation Street and Doctor Who]</ref>\n\nTosh was the [[script editor|story editor]] for the ''Doctor Who'' stories between ''[[The Time Meddler]]'' and ''[[The Massacre of St Bartholomew's Eve]]'', working with producers [[Verity Lambert]] and [[John Wiles]]. On Tosh's final story, ''[[The Massacre of St Bartholomew's Eve]]'' by [[John Lucarotti]], Tosh performed a substantial rewrite of the scripts, both to align them with historical accuracy and also to accommodate [[William Hartnell]]'s dual role as both the Doctor and the Abbot of Amboise.<ref>http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/doctor-who-story-editor-donald-4282399</ref> On the final episode the story editor's credit was given over to his successor [[Gerry Davis (screenwriter)|Gerry Davis]] and Tosh was co-credited.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/massacre/detail.shtml</ref>\n\nHe also performed an extensive re-write of ''[[The Celestial Toymaker]]'' by [[Brian Hayles]]. Most of this work, however, was in turn rewritten by Davis. Tosh claimed that the [[List of Doctor Who items#T|trilogic game]] was the sole retention from his version of the script.<ref>'Script editing Who: interview with Donald Tosh', ''Doctor Who Magazine''. No. 191</ref>\n\n==Post Television==\nAfter leaving television Tosh worked for a time for [[English Heritage]].  He was Head Custodian of [[Sherborne Castle|Sherborne Old Castle]], [[Dorset]] and [[St Mawes]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/lifestyle/doctor-who-story-editor-donald-4282399</ref> He retired to [[Essex]].\n\nIn 2013 he appeared as an extra in ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]'', a drama about the making of the William Hartnell era of ''Doctor Who'', made to commemorate the show's 50th anniversary. The programme did not, however, depict a version of him as a character.\n\nTosh died in December 2019 at the age of 84.<ref>[http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2019/12/donald-tosh-1935-2019.html Donald Tosh 1935\u20132019]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0869162}}\n{{Doctor Who}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tosh, Donald}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:British science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British soap opera writers]]\n[[Category:British television writers]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Tosh"}
{"title_page": "Erik Olin Wright", "text_new": "{{short description|American sociologist}}\n{{use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Erik Olin Wright\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = ErikOlinWright.2013.jpg\n| caption            = Erik Olin Wright lecturing at the [[Taras Shevchenko National University of Kyiv]] in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1947|2|9}}\n| birth_place        = [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]], U.S.\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| death_date         =  {{death date and age|2019|1|23|1947|2|9}}\n| death_place        = [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| region             = \n| nationality        = [[United States]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| title              = \n| spouse             = \n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = http://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/\n| alma_mater         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Harvard College]] ([[B.A.]] 1968)\n* [[Balliol College, Oxford]] ([[B.A.]] 1970)\n* [[University of California, Berkeley]] ([[Ph.D.]] 1976)<ref name=\"cv\" />\n}}\n| thesis_title       = Class Structure and Income Inequality<ref name=\"diss\" />\n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = 1976\n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = [[Arthur Stinchcombe]]{{sfn|Wright|1976|p=xiv}}\n| academic_advisors  = [[Michael Reich]]{{sfn|Wright|1976|p=xiv}}\n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = [[Sociologist]]\n| sub_discipline     = [[Analytic Marxism]]\n| workplaces         = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] (1976\u20132019)\n| doctoral_students  = {{plainlist|\n* {{ill|Andrew Szasz|de}}\n* {{ill|Adam Szetela|de}}\n* [[Wilmot James]]\n* [[George Steinmetz (academic)|George Steinmetz]]\n* {{ill|Karen Shire|de}}\n* [[Julia Adams (sociologist)|Julia Adams]]\n* [[Josh Whitford]]\n* [[C\u00e9sar Rodr\u00edguez Garavito]]<ref name=dissent />\n* [[Vivek Chibber]]\n}}\n| notable_students   = {{plainlist|\n* [[G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen]]<ref name=\"geadiss\" />\n* [[Eduardo Bonilla-Silva]]<ref name=\"ebsdiss\" />\n* [[Shamus Khan]]<ref name=dissent />\n* [[Devah Pager]]<ref name=dissent />\n* [[Lane Kenworthy]]<ref name=\"kenworthybook\" />\n}}\n| main_interests     = [[Class analysis#Class Size|Marxist class analysis]]\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Erik Olin Wright''' (February 9, 1947 \u2013 January 23, 2019) was an [[United States|American]] [[Analytical Marxism|analytical Marxist]] [[sociology|sociologist]] and educator, specializing in [[social stratification]], and in egalitarian alternative futures to [[capitalism]]. He was known for diverging from classical Marxism in his breakdown of the working class into subgroups of diversely held power and therefore varying degrees of class consciousness. Wright introduced novel concepts to adapt to this change of perspective including deep democracy and [[interstitial revolution]].<ref name=\"utopias\" />\n\n== Personal life and career ==\nErik Olin Wright was born on February 9, 1947, in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]] though he was raised in [[Lawrence, Kansas]]. Wright's parents were both psychology professors at the [[University of Kansas]].<ref name=ssobit>{{cite web |url=https://www.socialsciencespace.com/2019/01/the-pragmatic-utopian-erik-olin-wright-1947-2019/ |title=The Pragmatic Utopian: Erik Olin Wright, 1947-2019 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=January 28, 2019 |website=Social Science Space |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>  His parents were both Jewish.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} He received two B.A. degrees, one from [[Harvard College]] in 1968, and one from [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford]] in 1970.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} Wright received a Ph.D. from [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1976.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} He became a Professor of Sociology at [[University of Wisconsin - Madison]]<ref name=\"cv\" /> in 1976.<ref name=\"frankfurt\" />\n\nWright began making contributions to the intellectual community in the mid-1970s, along with a whole generation of young academics who were radicalized by the [[Vietnam War]] and the [[civil rights movement]].<ref name=\"ritzer\" />\n\nAt the University of Wisconsin-Madison, Wright supervised the dissertations of numerous young scholars who proceeded to become notable sociologists and politicians, among whom are included [[Wilmot James]], [[C\u00e9sar Rodr\u00edguez Garavito]], and [[Vivek Chibber]].<ref name=dissent /> Wright also served on the dissertation committees of scholars who go on to make considerable contributions to the fields of [[social stratification]], social policy, and inequality including [[G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen]], former American Sociological Association president [[Eduardo Bonilla-Silva]], and the late [[Devah Pager]].\n\nThroughout Wright's career, he was solicited by other universities to join their sociology faculty.<ref name=dissent /> One notable such recruitment attempt occurred at [[Harvard University]] in 1981. Among Wright's supporters were [[Harrison White]], who respected Wright's work despite opposition to Wright's Marxist political commitments. Wright's opponents at Harvard included [[Daniel Bell]] and [[George Homans]], as well as university president [[Derek Bok]] who purportedly blocked the department's attempt to recruit Wright.<ref name=nyttenure>{{cite news |last=Schumer |first=Fran R. |date=October 18, 1981 |title=A Question of Sex Bias at Harvard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/10/18/magazine/a-question-of-sex-bias-at-harvard.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |access-date= }}</ref> Harvard's attempt to recruit Wright coincided with its decision to deny tenure in 1981 to [[Theda Skocpol]], a decision that was later reversed following controversy over accusations of gender discrimination.<ref name=nytskocpol>{{cite news |last=Sanger |first=David E. |date=January 8, 1985 |title=Harvard Reverses Tenure Decision |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/08/us/harvard-reverses-tenure-decision.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York |access-date= }}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, Wright was elected President of the [[American Sociological Association]].<ref name=\"conf\" />\n\nWright died on January 23, 2019, from [[acute myeloid leukemia]] at a hospital in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], aged 71.<ref name=dissent /><ref name=\"madison\" />\n\nWright was also an avid [[fiddle]] player, often encouraging guests to [[square dance]] at parties.<ref name=\"tribute\" />\n\n== Thought ==\n{{original research|section|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Social classes ===\nWright has been described as an \"influential [[new left]] theorist\".<ref name=\"meiksins\" /> His work was concerned mainly with the study of [[social class]]es, and in particular with the task of providing an update to and elaboration of the [[Marxist]] concept of class, in order to enable Marxist and non-Marxist researchers alike to use \"class\" to explain and predict people's material interests, lived experiences, living conditions, incomes, organizational capacities and willingness to engage in [[collective action]], political leanings, and so on. In addition, he attempted to develop class categories that would allow researchers to compare and contrast the class structures and dynamics of different [[Advanced capitalism|advanced capitalist]] and \"[[post-capitalist]]\" societies.\n\nWright has stressed the importance of:\n# control over and exclusion from access to economic/productive resources;\n# location within production relations;\n# market capacity in exchange relations;\n# differential control over income derived from the use of productive resources; and,\n# differential control over labor effort in defining 'class', while at the same time trying to account for the situation of expert, skilled, manager, and supervisory employees, taking inspiration from [[Max Weber|Weberian]] accounts of class and class analysis.\n\nAccording to Wright, employees with sought-after and reward-inelastically supplied skills (due to natural scarcities or socially constructed and imposed restrictions on supply, such as licensing, barriers to entry into training programs, etc.) are in a \"privileged [surplus] appropriation location within exploitation relations\" because, while they are not capitalists, they are able to obtain more privileges through their relation to the owner of the means of production than less skilled workers and harder to monitor and evaluate in terms of labor effort. The owner(s) of the means of production or their employer in general therefore has to pay them a \"scarcity\" or \"skill/credential\" rent (thus raising their compensation above the actual cost of producing and reproducing their [[Labour power|labor power]]) and tries to \"buy\" their loyalty by giving them ownership stakes, endowing them with delegated authority over their fellow workers and/or allowing them to more or less be autonomous in determining the pace and direction of their work. Thus, experts, managers of experts, and executive managers tend to be closer to the interests of the employers than to other workers.\n\nErik Olin Wright's books include ''Class Counts: Comparative Studies in Class Analysis'' (Cambridge, 1997), which uses data collected in various industrialized countries, including the United States, Canada, Norway, and Sweden. He was a professor of sociology at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] until his death.\n\n=== Real utopias ===\nLater in his career, Wright was associated with a renewed understanding of a [[socialism|socialist]] alternative, deeply rooted on social [[associativism]].<ref name=\"RU\" /> The transition to this alternative, according to Wright, depends on designing and building \"[[Real utopian sociology|real utopias]]\", the name of a research project and book of his. Examples of \"real utopias\" that counter prevailing institutions by advancing democratic and egalitarian principles, thereby pointing in the direction of a more just and humane world, include [[Wikipedia]] and the [[Mondragon Corporation]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = The politics of punishment: a critical analysis of prisons in America | publisher = Harper & Row | location = New York | year = 1973 | isbn = 978-0-06-090318-3 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/politicsofpunish0000wrig }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Class, crisis, and the state | publisher = New Left Books | location = London | year = 1978 | isbn = 978-0-902308-93-0 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/classcrisisstate0000wrig }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Class structure and income determination | publisher = Academic Press | location = New York | year = 1979 | isbn = 978-0-12-764950-4 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/classstructurein0000wrig }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Classes | publisher = [[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 1997 | origyear = 1985 [[Verso Books|Verso]] | isbn = 978-1-85984-179-2 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = The debate on classes | publisher = [[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 1989 | isbn = 978-0-86091-966-7 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/debateonclasses0000unse }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Class counts: comparative studies in class analysis | publisher = Cambridge University Press Maison des Sciences de l'homme | location = Cambridge New York Paris | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-0-521-55646-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik | title = Envisioning real utopias | publisher =[[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-1-84467-617-0 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Alternatives to Capitalism: proposals for a democratic economy with Robin Hahnel (2014) New Left Project }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik | title = Understanding Class | publisher =[[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 2015 | isbn = 978-1-78168-945-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wright |first1=Erik Olin |title=How to Be an Anticapitalist in the Twenty-First Century |date=2019 |publisher=[[Verso Books]] |isbn=978-1-78873-605-3}}\n\n=== Collected works ===\n* {{cite book | last1 = Wright | first1 = Erik Olin | last2 = Fung | first2 = Archon | author-link2 = Archon Fung | title = Deepening democracy: institutional innovations in empowered participatory governance | publisher = [[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-1-85984-466-3 }}\n*:This is part of the [http://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/RealUtopias.htm Real Utopias Project]\n* {{cite book | last = Wright | first = Erik | title = Approaches to class analysis | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge, UK New York | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-0-521-60381-2 }}\n* Wright wrote the preface for: {{cite book | last1 = Gornick | first1 = Janet C. | last2 = Meyers | first2 = Marcia | title = Gender equality: transforming family divisions of labor | publisher = [[Verso Books|Verso]] | location = London New York | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-1-84467-325-4 }} Wright is also the book series' editor.\n\n=== Selected journal articles ===\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Wright | first1 = Erik Olin | last2 = Levine | first2 = Andrew | title = Rationality and class struggle | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = I | issue = 23 | publisher = New Left Review | date = September\u2013October 1980 | url = https://newleftreview.org/I/123/andrew-levine-erik-olin-wright-rationality-and-class-struggle | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Wright | first = Erik Olin | title = Compass points: towards a Socialist alternative | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 41 | publisher = New Left Review | date = September\u2013October 2006 | url = http://newleftreview.org/II/41/erik-olin-wright-compass-points | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Wright | first1 = Erik Olin | title = Transforming capitalism through real utopias | journal = [[American Sociological Review]] | volume = 78 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201325 | date = February 2013 | doi = 10.1177/0003122412468882 | ref = harv | url = https://www.aacademica.org/erik.olin.wright/5 }}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Theory of historical trajectory]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"conf\">{{cite web|title=American Sociological Association |url=http://www.asanet.org/AM2012/Chairconference.cfm |accessdate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504024007/http://www.asanet.org/AM2012/Chairconference.cfm |archivedate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ssc.wisc.edu/soc/faculty/CVs/Wright_CV_2016.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae |last=Wright |first=Erik Olin |date=June 2016 |website=[[University of Wisconsin, Madison]] Department of Sociology |publisher= |access-date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"diss\">{{cite thesis |last=Wright |first=Erik Olin |date=1976 |title=Class Structure and Income Inequality |type=Ph.D. |chapter= |publishe